The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal

 BRIEFS

 Burdwan, Feb. 16: The Burdwan admin- istration today said it would not allow the Jamait Ulema-i-Hind to hold a public meeting at Goda tomorrow. 

 A health city and a township are slated to be built at Goda, in the Burdwan municipal area, 110 km from Calcutta. The Jamait wants to protest against forced land acquisition. But additional district magistrate Subir Chatterjee said: The land belongs to the Burdwan Development Authority and no public meetings will be allowed there. 

 Kharagpur: An oil tanker broke down at a level crossing near here with two trains fast approaching on Friday. Nervous at the sight of vehicles clogged on the tracks, gateman Krishna Rao didnt know what to do. But local people took the initiative and ran with red flags in opposite directions to stop the Down Falaknama Express and a local train.

 Calcutta: Transport minister Subhas Chakraborty said a decision on reducing bus fares would be taken after consultations with the bus and mini bus unions. The bus syndicate said there were no grounds for a fare cut. Although the diesel price has come down to the October 2005 level, other costs have gone up.

 Behrampore: Residents of Natungram in Murshidabad, about 215 km from Calcutta, are spending sleepless nights because of a monkey. It has attacked at least five persons in the past five days.

 Calcutta: Labour minister Mrinal Banerjee has sought from the Centre more stringent laws to take on the owners of jute mills, on strike for months now.




